author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Despite a declared ceasefire, Palestinians in Gaza continue to face immense suffering. Hospitals are running out of medicine and medical supplies, leaving thousands without treatment. Patients with chronic illnesses say they can’t find or afford their medication. Many hospitals have been damaged or destroyed by Israeli bombardment, pushing Gaza’s already collapsing healthcare system to the brink. Displaced families continue to live in overcrowded tents that offer little protection from the heat or cold. Over one million Palestinians remain displaced, struggling daily for survival. For them, the ceasefire is not safety — it’s another phase of suffering and uncertainty.

Al Jazeera’s Hind Khoudary and Hani Mahmoud report from Gaza.

description:
Mohamad Elmasry, of the Doha Institute for Graduate Studies, says the fact that Trump appears to be personally invested in ending Israel’s war on Gaza is a positive sign that the conflict may indeed end. “What we’ve been saying for two years is that the United States holds all of the leverage. If they want the war to end, it will end,” Elmasry told Al Jazeera. “If Trump is so personally invested and has already made a determination that this is the end of the war, and if he’s made it clear to Israel that this is the end of the war, then I think we’re going to get the end of the war,” he added. Since Israel began its war on Gaza in October 2023, the US has provided its top ally with billions of dollars in military aid as well as unwavering diplomatic support. Both Trump and his predecessor, Joe Biden, had rebuffed calls to curb that assistance.

description:
Al Jazeera’s Charles Stratford reports from Doha, Qatar. He says we know that yesterday, Qatar’s top diplomat was in Paris meeting other foreign ministers and officials with respect to looking forward after this first phase of the Gaza ceasefire. He adds that if this ceasefire holds – hopefully – the next phase brings with it complications with respect to governance, eventual reconstruction, and things like the disarmament of Hamas. Stratford reports that a statement just released by Qatar states that Doha will be spearheading reconstruction efforts and humanitarian support in Gaza. It said it will include humanitarian grants, and it’s something both the US and Israel have accepted. They’ve accepted Qatar’s leadership in these efforts, interestingly, with respect to future governance and this thorny issue of some sort of interim authority in the Gaza Strip.

This week on an UpFront special, Marc Lamont Hill speaks with Guillaume Long, senior diplomatic adviser to the Hague Group and former Ecuadorian foreign minister.

Since returning to power more than four years ago in Afghanistan, the Taliban government has been gradually restricting the working rights of women. They  are permitted to hold jobs in only a few sectors of the economy, in what the UN is describing as the world’s worst women’s rights crisis.

Al Jazeera’s Rob McBride reports from Kabul.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
A tsunami alert has been issued after the Philippines was struck by a magnitude 7.4 earthquake, the second in less than 24 hours. The quake hit the southern Mindanao region at a depth of around 58 kilometres. Hazardous tsunami waves are possible for coastal areas. People are being urged to move to higher ground.

Al Jazeera’s Barnaby Lo joins live on the line from the capital, Manila.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Israel's government has approved the first phase of the Gaza ceasefire deal, which will come into effect within 24 hours.  The agreement should then see remaining captives exchanged for Palestinian prisoners, and a partial withdrawal of Israeli forces within the next three days. US president Donald Trump says the deal, agreed by Hamas, is a momentous breakthrough in the Middle East.

Al Jazeera’s Kimberly Halkett reports.
